The above code does not working, because you returned and assign the `&lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt; function XYZ() { //changing_body } XYZ();&lt;/script&gt;` string into a `chart1` div&#39;s inner HTML, which does not mean that it would create the new `&lt;script&gt;` tag with function override.

In short, the returned value is treated like a normal string of characters, and it is not correct way of adding new elements to DOM tree.

Furthermore, I was able to reproduce it without using .Net, in native JavaScript, and here is the example:
https://jsfiddle.net/qt1v6mof/

In order to get the expected effect, you should definitely use the document&#39;s [createElement][1] function in order to create a real `&lt;script&gt;` tag element, and then use [appendChild][2] to replace a current div&#39;s `innerHTML` content, like in below code and example:

```html
&lt;div id=&quot;chart&quot;&gt;
  &lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt;
 		var getMyChart = function() { alert(&quot;wow!&quot;); }
  &lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;button id=&quot;changeBtn&quot;&gt;Change getMyChart&#39;s body&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;callEndRequest&quot;&gt;Call endRequestHandler&lt;/button&gt;
```
```js
function change() {
	var newScript = document.createElement(&#39;script&#39;),
  	chartElem = document.getElementById(&#39;chart&#39;)
		
  chartElem.innerHTML = &#39;&#39;
  newScript.setAttribute(&#39;type&#39;, &#39;text/javascript&#39;);
  newScript.innerHTML = &#39;getMyChart = function() { alert(&quot;new body&quot;);}&#39;
  
  chartElem.appendChild(newScript)
}

function endRequestHandler () {
	getMyChart()
}

changeBtn.onclick = change
callEndRequest.onclick = endRequestHandler

getMyChart()
```

Live example: https://jsfiddle.net/9mdeoLb2/

Hope it will help
 you.
Kind regards!


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document/createElement
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Node/appendChild

